       <section class="grid-block" id="content">

          <div>
           <article class="post reveal-animation item" data-permalink="https://www.healthcatalyst.com/positive_healthcare_transformation/" style="margin-bottom: 40px">
            <header>
             <div class="grid-block">
              <div class="grid-box width100" style="margin-top: 15px;">
               <h1 class="title" style="padding-top: 0px; margin: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px">
                Whats Good About U.S. Healthcare
               </h1>
               <p>
                <i>
                 Written by
                 <a data-uk-modal="" href="#author-28">
                  Dr. John Haughom
                 </a>
                 . Posted in
                 <a href="/knowledge-center/search-results?type=category&amp;target=healthcare-transformation">
                  Healthcare Transformation
                 </a>
                </i>
               </p>
              </div>
              <div class="grid-box width100">
               <div class="grid-block">
                <div class="grid-box width100">
                 <div>
                  <div class="add-to-folder" data-permalink="https://www.healthcatalyst.com/positive_healthcare_transformation/" data-title="Whats Good About U.S. Healthcare" id="article_3628">
                   <div class="add-to-folder-img">
                   </div>
                   <div class="add-to-folder-text" data-add-text="Add To My Folder" data-added-text="Added">
                    Add To My Folder
                   </div>
                  </div>
                 </div>
                </div>
               </div>
              </div>
             </div>
            </header>
            <div class="content clearfix">
             <p>
              <a href="/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/iStock_000010703403XSmall.jpg">
               <img alt="iStock_000010703403XSmall" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-3630" height="300" src="/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/iStock_000010703403XSmall-250x300.jpg" width="250"/>
              </a>
              We hear a lot lately about the problems with healthcare in the United States. While the need to improve quality and decrease costs is real, lets not forget to celebrate what is good about the US healthcare system.
             </p>
             <p>
              In todays commentary, Id like to share a bit of history to emphasize one point: our healthcare is the best the world has ever seen!
             </p>
             <p>
              Consider these simple examples:
             </p>
             <ul>
              <li>
               From 1900 to 2010, average life expectancy at birth increased from only 49 years to almost 79 years.
              </li>
              <li>
               Since 1960, age-adjusted mortality from heart disease (the #1 cause of death) has decreased by 56 percent.
              </li>
              <li>
               Since 1950, age-adjusted mortality from stroke has decreased by 70 percent.
              </li>
             </ul>
             <p>
              Why so much progress over the last 100 years? Lets explore a few historical trends together.
             </p>
             <h2>
              The Emergence of Modern Medicine
             </h2>
             <p>
              For much of history, if you were ill or injured and saw a physician, your chances of survival actually went down. Hospitals were where people went to die. Actually, hospitals were where the poor went to die. If you had any resources at all, you invited a physician into your home  and you died at home.
             </p>
             <p>
              Just prior to 1900, this all changed profoundly. I credit the change to four impactful advances in the medical profession:
             </p>
             <ul>
              <li>
               New high standards of clinical education
              </li>
              <li>
               Strict requirements for professional licensing
              </li>
              <li>
               Clinical practice founded on scientific research
              </li>
              <li>
               New internal organization for hospitals
              </li>
             </ul>
             <p>
              Since that time, we in the medical profession routinely achieve miracles.
             </p>
             <h2>
              A Century of Strides in Public Health and Patient Care
             </h2>
             <p>
              Lets return to the change in life expectancy in the U.S. since 1900. The graph below shows that a child born in 1900 had a life expectancy of just shy of 50 years. For a child born 110 years later, the life expectancy is 78 yearsan increase of over 28 years! This is an amazing accomplishment and, frankly, something unseen in the prior 6000 years of recorded human history (where life expectancy remained relatively flat).
             </p>
             <p>
              <img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/>
             </p>
             <p>
              A lot of this increase can be attributed to improvements in public health. Thats why the first half of the 20
              <sup>
               th
              </sup>
              century could be called the Public Health Era. Because of public health advances, there was a gain of about 3.5 years in life expectancy with each passing decade. The increase was largely due to avoiding epidemics of infectious disease like cholera, typhus and smallpox.
             </p>
             <p>
              Then, sometime between 1950 and 1960, two things happened:
             </p>
             <ol>
              <li>
               We largely tapped out (though not completely) public health as a major source of increase in life expectancy.
              </li>
              <li>
               For the first time, we begin to document gains in life expectancy in the population as a whole from treatment provided in hospitals and clinics. Youll notice that the curve on the graph flattens out a bit at this pointa gain of about 1.3 years of life expectancy per decade. Though less than the public health increase, against the sweep of human history, the gain driven by clinical care is phenomenal.
              </li>
             </ol>
             <p>
              We stand on the foundation of 100 years of science that have massively improved our understanding of the human organism in health and disease and given us thousands of ways to improve the wellbeing and life expectancy of patients.
             </p>
             <p>
              Only in the last 60 years have we been able to show that clinical care can make a difference. This is in the lifetime of many people involved in healthcare today. We can do more than just predict whether a patient will live or die. We can actually change the outcome. We are the first generation of clinicians that can make that claim. Thats something that Im proud and excited to be a part of.
             </p>
             <h2>
              Why the History Lesson?
             </h2>
             <p>
              All of this history is important, because it changes how we think about the present and future. No doubt, we face many challenges. As healthcare increasingly contributes to the national debate, lets debate in the context of the phenomenal progress weve made and the progress were capable of making. And lets remember that
              <i>
               at least
              </i>
              <i>
               95 percent of our peer clinicians get up every day seeking to be the best they can be for the patients they serve
              </i>
              . They hold deep-seated professional expertise and a passion for quality that can be tapped as we seek to address the challenges and transform the system.
             </p>
             <p>
              What is good about the U.S. healthcare system from your perspective?
             </p>
            </div>

                 </a>
                </div>
                <div class="author text-left" style="font-family: 'Open Sans', Arial; font-size: 12px; font-weight: normal;">
                 <a data-uk-modal="" href="#author-28">
                  Dr. John Haughom
                 </a>
                </div>
                <!-- Author 28 Modal -->
                <div class="uk-modal uk-open" id="author-28" style="display: none; padding-right: 0px;">
                 <div class="uk-modal-dialog">
                  <a class="uk-modal-close uk-close">
                  </a>
                  <h3 class="module-title">
                   <img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-112" src="https://www.healthcatalyst.com/wp-content/uploads/userphoto/28.jpg" width="120"/>
                   Dr. John Haughom
                  </h3>
                  <p>
                   John Haughom, MD is an experienced healthcare executive with proven expertise in technology-enabled innovation, developing results-oriented strategic plans, leading multifaceted organization-wide change, and directing complex operations. He has a strong record of turning vision into effective strategies and successfully implementing initiatives resulting in value including higher quality, safer care at the lowest possible cost. His broad knowledge of healthcare and emerging healthcare technologies is coupled with his recognized leadership abilities, strong communication skills, and demonstrated ability to contribute to organizational goals such as improved clinical outcomes, lower costs, improved access to care, and increased profitability. After practicing for 15 years as an internist and gastroenterologist, Dr. Haughom assumed a senior executive role with responsibilities for system-wide automation, budgeting, customer support, database administration, healthcare delivery, information technology, quality control, research, safety, and strategic planning. Dr. Haughom became President and CEO of a firm focused on health care transformation through consulting, strategic planning, mentoring inexperienced physician leaders, involvement in regional and national reform movements, membership on boards of leading edge organizations committed to improving the value of healthcare, and partnership with other like-minded organizations with similar aspirations and goals.

As Senior Vice President of Clinical Quality and Patient Safety for the premiere health care system in the Northwest spanning three states (Oregon, Washington and Alaska), Dr. Haughom developed and implemented a system-wide quality improvement strategy, comprehensive patient safety plan, and comprehensive system-wide information technology strategy.
                  </p>
                 </div>

While the need to improve quality and decrease costs is real, let\u2019s not forget to celebrate what is good about the US healthcare system.\r\n\r\nIn today\u2019s commentary, I\u2019d like to share a bit of history to emphasize one point: our healthcare is the best the world has ever seen!\r\n\r\nConsider these simple examples:\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;From 1900 to 2010, average life expectancy at birth increased from only 49 years to almost 79 years.&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;Since 1960, age-adjusted mortality from heart disease (the #1 cause of death) has decreased by 56 percent.&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;Since 1950, age-adjusted mortality from stroke has decreased by 70 percent.&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n&lt;\/ul&gt;\r\nWhy so much progress over the last 100 years? Let\u2019s explore a few historical trends together.\r\n&lt;h2&gt;The Emergence of Modern Medicine&lt;\/h2&gt;\r\nFor much of history, if you were ill or injured and saw a physician, your chances of survival actually went down.\u00a0 Hospitals were where people went to die.\u00a0 Actually, hospitals were where the poor went to die.\u00a0 If you had any resources at all, you invited a physician into your home \u2026 and you died at home.\r\n\r\nJust prior to 1900, this all changed profoundly. I credit the change to four impactful advances in the medical profession:\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;New high standards of clinical education&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;Strict requirements for professional licensing&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;Clinical practice founded on scientific research&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;New internal organization for hospitals&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n&lt;\/ul&gt;\r\nSince that time, we in the medical profession routinely achieve miracles.\r\n&lt;h2&gt;A Century of Strides in Public Health and Patient Care&lt;\/h2&gt;\r\nLet\u2019s return to the change in life expectancy in the U.S. since 1900. The graph below shows that a child born in 1900 had a life expectancy of just shy of 50 years.\u00a0 For a child born 110 years later, the life expectancy is 78 years\u2014an increase of over 28 years! This is an amazing accomplishment and, frankly, something unseen in the prior 6000 years of recorded human history (where life expectancy remained relatively flat).\r\n\r\n&lt;img alt=\"\" \/&gt;\r\n\r\nA lot of this increase can be attributed to improvements in public health. That\u2019s why the first half of the 20&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;\/sup&gt; century could be called the Public Health Era. Because of public health advances, there was a gain of about 3.5 years in life expectancy with each passing decade. The increase was largely due to avoiding epidemics of infectious disease like cholera, typhus and smallpox.\r\n\r\nThen, sometime between 1950 and 1960, two things happened:\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;We largely tapped out (though not completely) public health as a major source of increase in life expectancy.&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;For the first time, we begin to document gains in life expectancy in the population as a whole from treatment provided in hospitals and clinics. You\u2019ll notice that the curve on the graph flattens out a bit at this point\u2014a gain of about 1.3 years of life expectancy per decade.\u00a0 Though less than the public health increase, against the sweep of human history, the gain driven by clinical care is phenomenal.&lt;\/li&gt;\r\n&lt;\/ol&gt;\r\nWe stand on the foundation of 100 years of science that have massively improved our understanding of the human organism in health and disease and given us thousands of ways to improve the wellbeing and life expectancy of patients.\r\n\r\nOnly in the last 60 years have we been able to show that clinical care can make a difference. This is in the lifetime of many people involved in healthcare today. We can do more than just predict whether a patient will live or die. We can actually change the outcome. We are the first generation of clinicians that can make that claim. That\u2019s something that I\u2019m proud and excited to be a part of.\r\n&lt;h2&gt;Why the History Lesson?&lt;\/h2&gt;\r\nAll of this history is important, because it changes how we think about the present and future.\u00a0 No doubt, we face many challenges. As healthcare increasingly contributes to the national debate, let\u2019s debate in the context of the phenomenal progress we\u2019ve made and the progress we\u2019re capable of making. And let\u2019s remember that &lt;i&gt;at least&lt;\/i&gt; &lt;i&gt;95 percent of our peer clinicians get up every day seeking to be the best they can be for the patients they serve&lt;\/i&gt;. They hold deep-seated professional expertise and a passion for quality that can be tapped as we seek to address the challenges and transform the system.\r\n\r\nWhat is good about the U.S. healthcare system from your perspective?","post_title":"What\u2019s Good About U.S. Healthcare","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","post_password":"","post_name":"whats-good-about-u-s-healthcare-a-history-lesson","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2014-04-07 07:05:54","post_modified_gmt":"2014-04-07 13:05:54","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/www.healthcatalyst.com\/?p=3628","menu_order":0,"post_type":"post","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"3","filter":"raw","link":"https:\/\/www.healthcatalyst.com\/positive_healthcare_transformation\/","get_the_title":"What\u2019s Good About U.S. Healthcare","seo_title":"What is Good about the US Healthcare System?","title":"What is Good about the US Healthcare System?"};
